The devices to monitor people are increasingly being requested by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their child leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as illustrated by that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of matches but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has stirred up a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even though the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We strive to tell everyone that this is not espionage but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, who is one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," adds Pilin.
According to him, children should always know the purpose of using the box and how to use it in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to carry something like this on him, he will get rid of it.
'And even the youngest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control.'
"The mobile phones, which can be cut off like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very questionable.
"If it's a pre-arranged rapture, the author will do everything to ensure that the child has no electronic device that can locate him."
"Now it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," said the psychologist.
It also confesses that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an attack.
"The device can be set in such a way that it is on a regular basis after a specified period of time."
"In case the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the person concerned."
'The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who has slipped and is in an extended position without moving," says Cech.
According to him, smartphone phones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after being trained with a special software.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to the ones that are worn in the pendant of the size of a box of lighters or to the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Macro Weil's Pilina, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracer."
"Or he'll figure it out after a while, which gave the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used as self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
