A longer index than the ring is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the longest index than the ring are exposed to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our conclusions show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple risk test for prostate cancer, especially for men before 60 years old," proclaimed co-author of the Ros Eeles study, professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer test, including by combining genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the ring.
For them as for the 19% of those with fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before 60 years the risk decrease reached 87 per cent.
The length of the two fingers cited - trained during the prenatal period - indicates, inter alia, different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less than testosterone is a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him to think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
