These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
As the survey has been conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it follows changes in the attitude in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's survey in September and early October.
The first is the quite sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the South American Pacific (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has grown from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy has improved after a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, thus reducing the regional average (see table 2).
Some 44% of the region's respondents expressed satisfaction with how their country's democracy worked in practice; this is the same figure as last year but with a strong increase of 25% in 2001 (Figure 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but they were up high compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, economic problems in Latin America have shaken support for democracy.
While this has been good during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have experienced only a brief recession and have experienced a great recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped to protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty has increased only slightly in 2009 and has again fallen to 32 per cent this year.)
