A microbe tolerating arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, expands the field to find new life forms on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the unusual bacteria here on Earth, they say that this shows that life has possibilities beyond the major elements that have been considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can be developed either with phosphorus, or with arsenic."
"That is why it is very special, even though it is far from being a truly "foreign" way of life," commented Paul Davies C. W. of the University of Arizona, co-author of the report in the online edition of the journal Science.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But researchers have discovered that the bacteria, discovered in Lake Mono, California, is able to continue to develop after replacing the phosphorus with the arsenic.
"We wonder what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the State University of Arizona, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life looks like, says Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss it, which did not disclose the details of the finding, generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of an alien life.
That was not the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other global environments, organisms could be able to use other elements to act on biochemistry and that the "standard" set of elements, which we consider absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," commented Charles Cockell, professor at the Institute of Planetary and Space Scientific Research, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another in fundamental biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random discovery.
Felicia Wolfe-Simon, NASA Institute of Astrology, who led the study, chose Lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, it speculated that one microbe exposed to both substances could be able to replace each other.
"Arsenic is mainly toxic because its chemical behavior is really similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, organizations have difficulty distinguishing these elements separately."
"But the arsenic is different enough so it doesn't work exactly like the phosphorus; it penetrates inside and somehow erases the work of our biochemical machine," explained Anbar.
Researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed it to increasing arsenic concentrations to which it was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with the phosphorus but the fact that it can live with the arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using the arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or the moon where the arsenic is more frequent.
Jamie S. Foster, Deputy Professor of Microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea, that the arsenic could be replaced by the phosphorus, was not new; but nothing ever showed that this could work.
The arsenic was more common at the beginning of Earth's existence, she said; thus, researchers have made the assumption that the first forms of life could have used it.
This suggests that there could be other ways to form life, not only the way life on Earth was formed at the beginning," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
