The prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The prosecutors of the Ministry of Justice lifted the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case related to a former campaign assistant and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the woman's husband, announced on Wednesday the Senator's lawyers.
The decision put an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican of Nevada who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential until the scandal surrounding his case did not make the major national titles last year and harm his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said he was "very happy" by the decision, the result of a one-year survey.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Department of Justice had "reported that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this case."
The Ministry of Justice has refrained from commenting on this issue.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise to many ethical lawyers outside the Ministry of Justice, according to which there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a lucrative lobbying job to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the Senator's case with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as a treasurer during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political donors to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law for a year from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, seemed in contradiction with the so-called lobbying door ban.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the law of the rotating door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department's judge refused to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in Ensign, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be suspicious of political prosecutions after a number of high-level charges by its section of public integrity, including decisions taken last year to abandon prosecutions against former Senator Ted Stevens for lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the general director of citizens for responsibility and ethics in Washington, a defence group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Senior Lawyer of Mr. Ensign, stated in an interview that he had received a telephone call from a prosecutor from Monday's Department of Justice and a follow-up the following day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against its client.
Mr. Ensign's lawyer team had cooperated with the prosecutors to try to convince them that the senator, as her office reaffirmed in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the public prosecutor's office.
"I am not comfortable entering into the details of my discussions with the Ministry of Justice, except to say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to abandon an inquiry following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the payment of $96,000 by Mr.Ensign's parents to Hampton violated federal electoral law.
The Electoral Commission stated that it did not have sufficient evidence to prove that the money was all except a gift.
NV Energy, an important Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
