Mr. Ensign also participated in a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and he asked the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had engaged Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his voters and resigned from his position as leader in the fourth Republican rank in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to fight a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, said that the honourable senator hoped that the Ethics Committee would follow the example of the Ministry of Justice quickly and put an end to his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
