Faced with this development, anxiety has increased with the veterans of the Red Khmers of Anlong Veng; complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to re-enter Cambodian society.
"There are resentments and fear among the former Khmer Reds but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent agency that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Red Khmers was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
Under the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overbeing.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrown the Pol Pot-U.S. government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to the border of Cambodia with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last of the movements arrived in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary were leading the guerrillas of their base located in the western mountains of Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a suite in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a United Nations-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Khmer fighters began to undermine the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had taken the lead, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most of the old Khmer Red veterans have suffocated in black poverty, common to the rural regions of Cambodia; and many of them remain nostalgic to the movement.
Although some Khmer-Red elite officers have kept their positions as local leaders in exchange for depositing the weapons, they are unskilled farmers at low grade and low grade.
