A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
Yesterday in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (GES) which corresponds to nearly one third of the additional reduction to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding commitments to reduce by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet to enlighten humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, large issuer countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to move global GHG emissions from 53 GT to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract another 5 Gt balance in order to stabilize by 2020 the increase in climate at 2 degrees to avoid it becoming out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, 5%, produced by light.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average between 6000 and 10 000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the United Nations study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats as well as very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have posted reservations for fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and they need to be eliminated as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place requirements.
But the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not fluocompact bulb, but rather coal thermal plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it $2.5 billion.
