Hackers revengers and spies in due course
WikiLeaks has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears only as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation that each file consisting of a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press cuts.
The "extraordinary" U.S. revelations on Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those whose Berlusconi owns), and Khadafi's caricature sinister profile was for a long time for skitch cabaret artists.
The rule that secret records should be composed only new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of secret services, not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Graal, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templiers or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in the previous works.
And not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (he doesn't know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who go to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who confirms what they have already learned.
It's Dan Brown's success mechanism.
Same for secret files.
The informer is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the chief of secret services (unless it could be, I know, editor at Libération), which retains only what he recognizes.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the American Embassy of Rome sent to the State Department was the same as the newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since Heads of State can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become centres of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it's only through hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy under bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the state department.
So the scandal does not put as many victims as the "burreaux" in crisis.
But let us come to the deep nature of what has happened.
So, in Orwell's time, we could conceive all power like a Big Brother who was controlling every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy has been fully proven since, in order to control each movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the borrowed highway and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the power eye.
But when it is demonstrated, as now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the revenger of the citizen - may know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the opportunity to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means taking all power away from him.
WikiLeaks did nothing wrong with Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big for Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this highly powerful injury?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put on-line any information reserved - that would be published on a poster stuck around the street.
But it is as obvious as with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential relationships by telephone.
Nothing easier than discovering whether and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and is therefore Romanesque, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who travel discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable itineraries, bearing only messages learned by heart or, at the very least, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in key closed drawers: at the bottom, Watergate's spying attempt has been less successful than WikiLeaks.
I have had the opportunity to write that technology is now advanced in crabs, that is to say back.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized the communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
Videocassettes (analogics) had enabled cinema researchers to explore a step-by-step film, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the CDs (numerics) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroporations.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while on the plane, and the travels it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communication policy and techniques return to the horse cars.
