Climate: How France Bidouille Promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review compliance with the fast-disbursed financing promises (such fast-start or early funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French biduillages are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (EUR 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU came out of the great game to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its Member States, press conference, large side event, brochure distribution...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated for its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same level of precision.
The EU announces that in 2010 €2.2 billion has been released, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look into detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States whose proceedings have been blocked by France.
Today, each one chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years to fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of "all new projects" of the year 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element, the distribution between gifts and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that €1 lent is equal to €1 given.
Of course, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation based on more efficient technologies), it is not possible to present a euro that will be recovered as an equivalent to a euro given... At the very least, it should be counted on under its commitments only the cost of the loan for the lender country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France only makes such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (in others) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts €1 to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-and-pass tour!
In short, in its fast start funding, France operates a double fraud: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, she can claim that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has achieved arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations as developing countries are not completely of the...
The chapter on early funding is only a relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year's early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of compliance with its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of a nature to increase the level of international confidence needed to advance in the discussions.
